WEBVTT

00:21.060 --> 00:23.860
CHAPTER XVIII.

00:23.860 --> 00:29.440
Narrative continued by the Doctor. End of the first day's fighting.

00:32.540 --> 00:39.280
We made our best speed across the strip of wood that now divided us from the stockade,

00:40.640 --> 00:45.320
and at every step we took the voices of the buccaneers rang nearer.

00:47.340 --> 00:53.240
Soon we could hear their footfalls as they ran and the cracking of the branches

00:53.240 --> 00:56.360
as they breasted across a bit of thicket.

01:01.720 --> 01:08.000
I began to see we should have a brush for it in earnest and looked to my priming.

01:09.800 --> 01:17.640
Captain, said I, Trenolny is the dead shot. Give him your gun. His own is useless.

01:19.240 --> 01:26.900
They exchanged guns and Trenolny, silent and cool as he had been since the beginning of the bustle,

01:28.100 --> 01:32.400
hung a moment on his heel to see that all was fit for service.

01:33.920 --> 01:40.920
At the same time, observing Grey to be unarmed, I handed him my cutlass.

01:41.660 --> 01:46.020
It did all our hearts good to see him spit in his hand,

01:47.240 --> 01:51.420
knit his brows and make the blade sing through the air.

01:52.700 --> 01:58.260
It was plain from every line of his body that our new hand was worth his salt.

02:02.420 --> 02:09.040
Forty paces farther, we came to the edge of the wood and saw the stockade in front of us.

02:10.000 --> 02:16.980
We struck the enclosure about the middle of the south side and almost at the same time,

02:17.500 --> 02:26.120
seven mutineers, Job Anderson, the Botswain at their head, appeared in full cry at the southwestern corner.

02:28.240 --> 02:35.380
They paused as if taken aback and before they recovered, not only the Squire and I,

02:35.380 --> 02:39.660
but Hunter and Joyce from the blockhouse had time to fire.

02:41.180 --> 02:48.520
The four shots came in rather a scattering volley, but they did the business. One of the

02:48.520 --> 02:55.540
enemy actually fell and the rest, without hesitation, turned and plunged into the trees.

02:58.240 --> 03:04.600
After reloading, we walked down the outside of the palisade to see to the fallen enemy.

03:05.380 --> 03:08.820
He was stone dead, shot through the heart.

03:12.000 --> 03:19.980
We began to rejoice over our good success when just at that moment a pistol cracked in the bush.

03:21.120 --> 03:29.260
A ball whistled close past my ear and poor Tom Rudrith stumbled and fell his length on the ground.

03:30.540 --> 03:39.180
Both the Squire and I returned the shot, but as we had nothing to aim at, it is probable we only

03:39.180 --> 03:45.000
wasted powder. Then we reloaded and turned our attention to poor Tom.

03:47.900 --> 03:53.940
The Captain and Gray were already examining him and I saw with half an eye that all was over.

03:56.760 --> 04:03.800
I believe the readiness of our return volley had scattered the mutineers once more,

04:04.660 --> 04:11.960
for we were suffered without further molestation to get the poor old gamekeeper hoisted over the

04:11.960 --> 04:17.660
stockade and carried, groaning and bleeding, into the log house.

04:19.680 --> 04:29.340
Poor old fellow. He had not uttered one word of surprise, complaint, fear, or even acquiescence

04:29.340 --> 04:37.460
from the very beginning of our troubles till now. When we had laid him down in the log house to die,

04:38.860 --> 04:46.100
he had lain like a Trojan behind his mattress in the gallery. He had followed every order silently,

04:46.980 --> 04:52.520
doggedly, and well. He was the oldest of our party by a score of years,

04:53.480 --> 05:01.040
and now sullen, old, serviceable servant. It was he that was to die.

05:03.520 --> 05:10.340
The Squire dropped down beside him on his knees and kissed his hand, crying like a child.

05:14.360 --> 05:23.160
Be I going, Doctor? he asked. Tom, my man, said I. You're going home.

05:25.720 --> 05:30.240
I wish I had a lick at them with the gun first, he replied.

05:32.540 --> 05:37.520
Tom, said the Squire, say you forgive me, won't you?

05:38.480 --> 05:44.060
Would that be respectful, like, from me to you, Squire, was the answer.

05:45.660 --> 05:48.720
Howsoever, so be it. Amen.

05:51.600 --> 05:57.460
After a little while of silence, he said he thought somebody might read a prayer.

05:58.700 --> 06:02.900
It is the custom, sir, he added apologetically.

06:04.140 --> 06:08.820
And not long after, without another word, he passed away.

06:11.300 --> 06:18.240
In the meantime, the captain, whom I had observed to be wonderfully swollen about the chest and

06:18.240 --> 06:29.040
pockets, had turned out a great many various stores. The British Colors, a Bible, a coil of

06:29.040 --> 06:36.120
Scottish rope, pen, ink, the log book, and pounds of tobacco.

06:38.260 --> 06:44.320
He had found a longish fir tree lying felled and trimmed in the enclosure,

06:45.560 --> 06:50.440
and with the help of Hunter, he had set it up at the corner of the log house,

06:51.140 --> 06:53.280
where the trunks crossed and made an angle.

06:54.980 --> 07:02.800
Then, climbing on the roof, he had with his own hand bent and run up the Colors.

07:05.300 --> 07:13.480
This seems mightily to relieve him. He re-entered the log house and set about counting up the stores

07:13.480 --> 07:20.780
as if nothing else existed. But he had an eye on Tom's passage for all that.

07:21.740 --> 07:30.560
And as soon as all was over, he came forward with another flag and reverently spread it on the body.

07:32.820 --> 07:38.460
Don't you take on, sir, he said, shaking the squire's hand.

07:39.920 --> 07:47.700
All's well with him. No fear for a hand that's been shot down in his duty to captain and owner.

07:48.640 --> 07:55.280
It mayn't be good divinity, but it's a fact. Then he pulled me aside.

07:58.540 --> 08:05.340
Dr. Livesey, he said, in how many weeks do you and Squire expect the consort?

08:07.920 --> 08:15.520
I told him it was a question not of weeks, but of months, that if we were not back by the end of

08:15.520 --> 08:24.780
August, Blanley was to send to find us. But neither sooner nor later. You can calculate

08:24.780 --> 08:34.280
for yourself, I said. Why, yes, returned the captain, scratching his head. And making a

08:34.280 --> 08:41.580
large allowance, sir, for all the gifts of Providence, I should say we were pretty close-hauled.

08:44.440 --> 08:47.260
How do you mean? I asked.

08:49.060 --> 08:51.680
It's a pity, sir. We lost that second load.

08:52.600 --> 08:58.640
That's what I mean, replied the captain. As for powder and shot will do.

08:59.740 --> 09:06.620
The rations are short. Very short. So short, Dr. Livesey.

09:06.780 --> 09:10.020
There were perhaps as well without that extra mouth.

09:11.680 --> 09:14.960
And he pointed to the dead body under the flag.

09:19.340 --> 09:26.660
Just then, with a roar and a whistle, a round shot passed high above the roof

09:26.660 --> 09:30.820
of the log house and plumped far beyond us in the wood.

09:32.580 --> 09:40.080
Oh ho, said the captain, blaze away. You've little enough powder already, my lads.

09:42.780 --> 09:48.840
At the second trial, the aim was better. And the ball descended inside the stockade,

09:50.460 --> 09:54.040
scattering a cloud of sand, but doing no further damage.

09:55.600 --> 10:01.900
Captain, said the squire, the house is quite invisible from the ship.

10:03.120 --> 10:08.840
It must be the flag they are aiming at. Would it not be wiser to take it in?

10:09.680 --> 10:15.000
Strike my colors, cried the captain. No, sir, not I.

10:16.060 --> 10:20.920
And as soon as he had said the words, I think we all agreed with him.

10:21.660 --> 10:26.320
For was not only a piece of stout, seemingly good feeling,

10:27.740 --> 10:34.580
it was good policy besides and showed our enemies that we despised their cannonade.

10:37.620 --> 10:42.200
All through the evening, they kept thundering away.

10:43.060 --> 10:49.860
Ball after ball flew over or fell short, or kicked up the sand in the enclosure.

10:51.960 --> 10:58.480
But they had to fire so high that the shot fell dead and buried itself in the soft sand.

11:00.100 --> 11:07.120
We had no ricochet to fear. And though one popped in through the roof of the log house,

11:07.220 --> 11:12.680
and out again through the floor, we soon got used to that sort of horseplay,

11:13.320 --> 11:15.320
and minded it no more than cricket.

11:18.200 --> 11:22.380
There is one good thing about all of this, observed the captain.

11:24.200 --> 11:30.020
The wood in front of us is likely clear. The ebb has made a good while.

11:31.260 --> 11:36.220
Our stores should be uncovered. Volunteers to go and bring in pork?

11:39.080 --> 11:45.020
Gray and Hunter were the first to come forward. While armed, they stole out of the stockade,

11:45.900 --> 11:52.360
but approved a useless mission. The mutineers were bolder than we fancied.

11:53.100 --> 11:55.940
Or they put more trust in Israel's gunnery.

11:58.440 --> 12:02.260
For four or five of them were busy carrying off our stores

12:02.260 --> 12:06.840
and waiting out with them to one of the gigs that lay close by.

12:08.860 --> 12:12.280
Pulling an oar sewed to hold her steady against the current.

12:14.460 --> 12:22.100
Silver was in the stern, sheets in command. And every man of them was now provided with a musket.

12:22.380 --> 12:25.280
From some secret magazine of their own.

12:28.580 --> 12:33.600
The captain sat down to his log, and here is the beginning of the entry.

12:37.080 --> 12:43.480
Alexander Smollett, master. David Livesey, ship's doctor.

12:45.560 --> 12:51.920
Abraham Gray, carpenter's mate. John Trinolny, owner.

12:54.620 --> 13:04.120
John Hunter and Richard Joyce, owner-servants, landsmen. Being all that is left faithful of the

13:04.120 --> 13:12.800
ship's company, with stores for ten days at short rations, came ashore this day and flew British

13:12.800 --> 13:21.960
colors on the log house in Treasure Island. Thomas Redruth, owner-servant, landsman.

13:22.680 --> 13:28.340
Shot by the mutineers. James Hawkins, cabin boy.

13:30.820 --> 13:35.360
And at the same time, I was wondering over poor Jim Hawkins's fate.

13:37.580 --> 13:39.000
A hail on the land side.

13:41.760 --> 13:45.580
Somebody's hailing us, said Hunter, who was on guard.

13:47.020 --> 13:54.840
Doctor! Squire! Captain! Hello, Hunter! Is that you? came the cries.

13:56.980 --> 14:07.420
And I ran to the door in time to see Jim Hawkins, safe and sound, come climbing over the stockade.

14:11.680 --> 14:13.380
End of chapter 18

